import numpy as np
def vectorize_sequences(sequences, dimension=10000):
    results = np.zeros((len(sequences), dimension))
    for i, sequence in enumerate(sequences):
        for j in sequence:
            results[i, j] = 1.
    return results

#Constructing a model with relu and compiling it
#This is the most basic setup you will ever see: our labels are scalars (1 and 0s) and our input data are just vectors. For such a task, a simple network architecture consisting of fully-connected (Dense) layers with relu activations is effective. Dense(16, relu activation).
#At last, decide on an optimizer and a loss function. We should use the binary_crossentropy loss because we are working with a binary classification problem and the output of our network is a probability (we end up with a single-unit layer with sigmoid activation).
from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import layers

model = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(16, activation="relu"),
    layers.Dense(16, activation="relu"),
    layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")
])
